After M has James Bond shot on a mission, he is presumed dead and goes into hiding. But when M and M16 are attacked by an unknown cyber terrorist, he returns to London. Rusty at the spy game, he manages to track down and capture the cyber terrorist: Raoul Silva, a former M16 operative under M. But Raoul escapes and tricks M16 into letting him hack their systems. James pursues Raoul who hunts after M. James gets her and together hey head to the manor where James had grown up as an orphan. With the help of his old friend Kincade, they prepare for Raoul. Raoul and his agents arrive and after an emotional battle James kills Raoul, but at a cost: the manor is destroyed and M is killed, Raoul essentially winning. In the aftermath, M is replaced by Gareth Mallory.
Sam Mendes does an phenomenally extraordinary job of directing the film, with the film having countless jaw-dropping, Oscar-worthy visuals, especially during the climax of the movie. The acting is great; Daniel Craig and Javier Bardem are clearly having amazing time, with Daniel Craig seeming refreshed by better material and Javier Bardem playing a malicious antagonist. The action scenes are thrilling and the climax is incredible, save the fact that it ends with no hand-to-hand combat between James Bond and Raoul Silva. There are also some abrupt and mishandled character/story arcs, but nothing that you notice until after the flick. The feature does do a good job of making James Bond vulnerable and giving him emotions he hasn‚Äôt shown in the previous two films in the franchise.
All in all, Skyfall, is an epic film.

